Science

One heuristic I like is:

Every scientific breakthrough either discovered a new invariant or found the correct resolution at which an old invariant became visible.

Examples include:

* Microscopes revealing cells.
* Telescopes revealing galaxies.
* Better detectors revealing new particles.
* Higher-resolution measurements exposing subtle material properties.

The instruments changed, but so did the effective resolution of the questions scientists could ask.

⸻

Innovation

I think there’s an overlooked search strategy:

Don’t search only for adjacent ideas.

Search for adjacent resolutions.

When stuck:

* Zoom out until different fields become structurally comparable.
* Extract the invariant.
* Zoom back in and instantiate it in the target domain.

That gives you a disciplined version of cross-domain analogy: use broader abstractions to generate hypotheses, then return to the specific domain to test them.

